# Project Rules for BallGames

## Tech Stack
- Use Matter.js for 2D physics.
- Use HTML5 Canvas (or p5.js if preferred) for rendering.
- Keep the game mobile-first (responsive and touch-enabled).

## Physics Style
- "Squashy" Feel: Always use high restitution (0.6 - 0.8) and low friction.
- Same-sized balls should merge into the next level up upon collision.
- Ensure balls don't "clip" through the floor or walls during fast movement.

## Coding Preferences
- Write clean, vanilla JavaScript unless a library is requested.
- Use Pointer Events (pointerdown, pointermove) instead of Mouse Events to ensure Android compatibility.
- Keep the logic modular (e.g., separate functions for 'createBall', 'checkMerge', and 'updateScore').

## Mobile Integration
- Always include a viewport meta tag for mobile scaling.
- Ensure the game container fills the screen height without scrolling.